author: The University of Western Australia & Equonto Pty. Ltd.

creator.value: The University of Western Australia & Equonto Pty. Ltd.

contributor.value: Caitlin Woods: The University of Western Australia and Equonto

abstract.value: The OMPD Static Procedure Ontology captures static information found in most insdutrial maintenance procedures.

title.value: Ontology for Maintenance Procedure Documentation (OMPD) Static Procedure Ontology

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'quality' that can be characterised in terms of chemical properties.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of of "chemical properties" is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The steel grade of a cast-iron component, the plastic type of a wire sheathing.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'disposition', the realization of which serves a positive interest.

primitiveRationale.value: Making the notion of "positive interest" fully precise is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The capability of a pump to serve as an anchor (ISO 15926-2, section 5.2.24.2).

comment.undefined: In Merrell et al., 2022, 'capability' is defined in terms of "interest in", specifically as a "disposition in whose realization someone (or some organism, or some group of organisms) has or had an interest."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'artefact' that is a 'physical object'.

semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom.value: If x is a 'physical artefact', then x is an 'artefact' and a 'physical object'.

example.value: A worktable, a bolt, a digital display unit, a pressure vessel.

comment.undefined: The PCA RDS defines RDS422594 'artefact' as, "An inanimate physical object that is made or given shape by man."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A three-dimensional, connected 'spatial location'.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of geometries is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A volume designated for 3D engineering at a point in time, a box-shaped volume determined by coordinates in a 3D frame of reference; the extent of a gas leak at 12:00

definition.value: classifier used to specify the state of a resource in its development process

explanatoryNote.value: Release notes will be provided for any changes concerning released content, and any revisions will be backward compatible with the prior version to the degree possible.

definition.value: construct or ontology development state in which the resource is stable, usable, and has been made available to external users
construct or ontology development state in which content is subject to change and may change considerably

explanatoryNote.value: IOF users should be aware that the resource is not dependable, but can be used for reference and for further work.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A human 'organism'.

primitiveRationale.value: Providing precise semantics of what "human" amounts to is beyond the scope of IDO.

scopeNote.value: In industry use cases, subclasses of 'person' will typically require role attributions to be considered fully explicit. For example, 'maintenance engineer' is an obvious subclass of 'person', as every engineer is a person; use a 'role' to say what a maintenance engineer does. I.e., such a class may be augmented with a restriction to say that any member is the bearer of an engineering role; what the role amounts to will then be captured by the kinds of activities that count as realizations of the role.

example.value: A person, a child, an engineer.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An entity that is a concrete implementation of a 'prescriptive [entity]'.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of concrete implementation, of providing an actual item to serve a design, is not defined. An explication should be given in terms of systems engineering practices.

example.value: A serial-numbered artefact installed at a tag, a function of a concrete artefact, a run or execution of a designed process, an industrial facility "as built".

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A continuous period of time.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of temporal intervals is beyond the scope of IDO (temporal logic offers no obvious consensus).

example.value: The time an instrument has been in operation, the time during which a measurement was made.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000202 is 'temporal interval'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'physical object' that is not living.

primitiveRationale.value: An account of what "living" means is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A tool, a building, a vehicle, an instrument, a parking lot.

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2, p. 122: "A class_of_inanimate_physical_object is a class_of_arranged_individual whose members are not living."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An aggregate of one or more 'person's that 'has role' some 'role'.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of the notion of organization is beyond the scope of IDO (it would determine which kinds of aggregations of people, and which kinds of roles, are appropriate for organizations).

example.value: A standards body, a a service team, a workgroup

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A dependent entity that represents a potential of its bearer.  Realization is specified by a type of activity, and appropriate kind of participation: a necessary condition for realization is that the bearer of the potential participates, in the way specified, in an activity of the specified kind.

primitiveRationale.value: The necessary condition for being a 'potential' is that activity type and participation type are provided. It is however not clear what sufficient conditions would consist in, as these would at least involve a notion of successful execution for the relevant activities, which goes beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The storage-space role of a room, the sealing function of a gasket, the disposition to corrode of a steel bar.

comment.undefined: URI of the paper Arp and Smith, 2008, "Function, Role, and Disposition in Basic Formal Ontology".
An ISO:Role that is the role of an ISO:Object that is required to execute some ISO:Activity

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 4D region, extended in space as well as time.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of the notion of spacetime goes beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The spatiotemporal region occupied by the fluid contents of a vessel over a period of time, the spatiotemporal region occupied by a pipeline inspection device (pig) during an inspection.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000011 is 'spatiotemporal region'.
An ISO: Object that has some OMPD: Resource Role
An ISO: Activity that has the potential to cause harm
An ISO: Activity, intended to repair or restore an item to a state in which it can perform its required function

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'quality' that can be characterised in terms of spatial properties.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of of "spatial properties" is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The flat shape of a surface feature, the cylindrical shape of a piece of pipe.

usageNote.value: The class 'stream' is intended to be used for flows of material or energy, in accordance with conventional use. There is an abundance of cases where use of the term "stream" might be called into question, as in, is a stream of electricity really moving; how many cars are needed to participate before it is properly called a "flow" of cars; while a flow of sand is a stream, maybe a succession of rolling rocks would not qualify.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'inanimate physical object', consisting of energy or homogeneous parts, with velocity along a path determined by a 'site'.

primitiveRationale.value: An full account of the criteria for what counts as a stream is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A stream of fluid in a pipeline, electricity in an electrical wire, ore moving on a conveyor belt.

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2, p. 112, states, "A stream is a physical_object that is material or energy moving along a path, where the path is the basis of identity and may be constrained. The stream consists of the temporal parts of those things that are in the stream whilst they are in it."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'potential' for which realization depends on the physical make-up of the bearer. That is, when exposed for some time to some appropriate kind of physical environment, the bearer will participate in activities that realize the disposition.

primitiveRationale.value: Making the notion of "appropriate physical environment" fully precise is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The disposition of a steel bar to corrode, the disposition of a gasket to leak.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000016 is 'disposition'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A zero-dimensional 'spatial location' with no proper parts.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of geometries is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The origo, the location of a probe at a given point in time

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An entity that is not dependent on other entities for existence, and which persists through time.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of what counts as an 'object' is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A process plant, a compressor, a wire, an operator, a database record, an industry standard.

scopeNote.value: In IDO, ’information object’ is represented as a subclass of ’object’. According to the BFO literature, and applied in the Information Artifact Ontology and other BFO compliant ontologies, information artifacts are (multiply) dependent objects. a /sibling/ class to ’independent continuant’ rather than a subclass, as used in IDO.

comment.undefined: From the DOLCE description of 'endurant': "The main characteristic of endurants is that all of them are independent essential wholes. ..."

usageNote.value: The utility of a 'site' may be represented by assigning one or more 'role's, such as 'front desk role', 'storage space role', or 'entryway role'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A three-dimensional 'location', demarcated by material entities serving as boundaries or points of reference.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of the notion of demarcation is beyond the scope of IDO.

scopeNote.value: The position of a 'site' follows the position of the 'physical object' by which it is demarcated.
Locations such as countries and cities are also considered sites.

example.value: An office, a flight deck, the inside of a manifold, the hold of a ship.

comment.undefined: This class is inspired by the BFO/Information Artefact Ontology class BFO_0000029 'site'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A one-dimensional, connected 'spatial location'.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of geometries is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A line connecting two points with coordinates relative to the frame of reference, the path of a flexible pipe at 12:00

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A living 'physical object'.

primitiveRationale.value: Providing precise semantics of what "living thing" amounts to is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: Animal, plant, fungus, bacterium.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A region in space.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of the notion of location is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: An outdoor plant area, an opening in a wall, the space inside an enclosure

comment.undefined: A ISO:Person that may have some OMPD:ResourceRole and has a OMPD:Qualification

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'object' with at least one function that can only be realized given that the functions of one or more parts are realized as well.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of the nature of dependency between the function of a system, as a whole, and the functions of its parts is (likely) beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A pressure vessel, a crane, a pipeline.

comment.undefined: TODO consider "accidental" dependency of system function on parts, versus "essential", with a composition relation between system function and the functions of parts.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An individual that has one or more separated intervals as parts.

primitiveRationale.value: (This class could be considered non-primitive, defined in terms of 'temporal region' and each part mapping by 'has temporal extent' to 'interval'.)

example.value: Intermittent times of operation of a heater, maintenance periods at a plant, times that a milling machine is run, The Saturdays of 2011, the construction period for a plant modification

comment.undefined: BFO_0000038 is 'one-dimensional temporal region' in BFO-ISO.

usageNote.value: Qualities are in general subject to change over the lifetime of the bearer. The main IDO device for representing quality changes is through 'datum' individuals: see lis:qualityQuantifiedAs.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'dependent [entity]' that is present (is actual) any time that the bearer exists.

explanatoryNote.value: In ISO 15926-2, the term "quality or characteristic" is used to explain what the entity type 'property' represents (section 5.2.26.5, notes 1 and 2). Note 2 reads, "The types of characteristic or quality, such as temperature or density, are instances of class_of_property."

primitiveRationale.value: Qualities cover a broad range of what is commonly referred to as "properties". It is beyond the scope of IDO to precisely determine what should be included.

example.value: The temperature of a fluid stream, the tensile strength of a bolt, the length of a pipeline, the colour of a surface coating, the familiarity of a specialist with a modification procedure, the quality of a window of being open or closed.

comment.undefined: The class Quality and its subclass PhysicalQuantity are inspired by corresponding classes included in the DOLCE and BFO (BFO_0000019) upper ontologies.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A definite magnitude of a 'quality', defined and adopted by convention or by law, that is used as a standard for measurement of the same kind of 'quality'. (rephrased from Wikipedia)

primitiveRationale.value: Precisely determining what qualifies as a unit of measure is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: centimetre, kilogram per minute, Celsius, lunar distance, kilo-lines of code

comment.undefined: UO_0000000 is 'unit', a class in the OBO Units of measure ontology.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'potential' which is an attitude of the bearer toward a potential activity.

primitiveRationale.value: Accounting for the notion of (mental) attitude is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A plan to act, an approval of a survey.

comment.undefined: A ISO:PhysicalObject that  may have some OMPD:ResourceRole

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'object' that is part of a specification.

explanatoryNote.value: The class 'prescriptive object' may be considered defined as "an individual that may appear on the right side of an 'installed as' relationship". It is in this sense not primitive.

primitiveRationale.value: An account of the nature of specifications is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: An equipment tag, a functional location (SAP), a maintenance schedule, a production area, a software program for instrument control, a CAD design.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A part of the flow of time, or something that takes place in time.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of time, and of the unfolding of events in time, is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A moment in time, a period of time, an activity or process, a beginning, a closing event.

comment.undefined: In Part 2, Activity is not a supertype of Event; in BFO, 'process' is not a supertype of 'process boundary'. This may indicate that 'event' in IDO should in fact not be a subclass of 'activity'.
A ISO:Quality that is beared by zero or more OMPD:QualitifiedPerson

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An item that is made during the software development process.

explanatoryNote.value: IAO_0000010 is 'software'. The Information Artifact Ontology includes the following subclasses: 'software application', 'software library', 'software method', 'software module', 'software script'.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of software development is not defined.

example.value: A CAD application, a SQL query, a backup script.

comment.undefined: An ISO:InformationObject that is about some OMPD:MaineanceProcedureProcess
An OMPD:MaintenanceProcess that is represented in some OMPD:MaintenanceProcedureDocument and has activity part some OMPD:MaintenanceTask

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'temporal' entity that 'has participant' some 'physical object'.

primitiveRationale.value: (Here we could consider saying the class is in fact not primitive, but defined in terms of 'temporal' and 'has participant'.)

scopeNote.value: An 'activity' doesn't need to be temporally connected. For example, intermittent operation of a heater over a week can be represented by a single 'activity' individual; it will occupy a non-connected 'interval region'. The details of each connected activity part ("singular activities") may be modelled by relating the activity to 'interval' individuals.

example.value: A pumping, an inspection, a report writing, a fastening (the activity of a bolt in holding two pieces together).

comment.undefined: In BFO-ISO, a constraint (as given in the elucidation, not in an OWL axiom) on 'process' is that it has "some temporal proper part". This is not included in IDO. On the contrary, we make 'event', which will have an instant as temporal extent, a subclass of 'activity'.

usageNote.value: This class may be used for data that don't fit the restriction to "single unit, single number" of 'scalar quantity datum', including data employing vectors instead of numbers, and conventional categories like "high" and "medium".

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'information object' that represents the magnitude of a 'quality'.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of the notion of representation of magnitudes is beyond scope of IDO.

scopeNote.value: Introduce subclasses of 'quality datum' in RDL to distinguish categories of data, such as nominal versus measured values.

example.value: 10 volts, high (of pressure), low (of temperature), category 3 (as used to rate the strength 'quality' of a storm), 3 MB (a file size).

comment.undefined: This class is inspired by the class "measurement datum" of the Information Artefact Ontology. The change of wording from "measurement" to "quality" is intended to support cases where measurement is not involved, such as with nominal values.

usageNote.value: Typically, a physical quantity of a participant, such as a "pressure" individual, is selected, and the "pressure profile" of the activity is introduced. The relation 'profile of quality' links to that pressure quality individual that defines (is the basis for abstraction to) the activity profile. By means of the relation 'profile quantity datum', the activity profile can be related to 'quantity datum' individuals, to which aggregation can be applied, giving a basis for classification of the activity profile; for example, as a "rising pressure" activity.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A part of an 'activity', a "selective abstraction" (cf. BFO reference) to just that part of the containing activity that consists in varying or maintaining a specified 'quality' of a participant.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of the notion of selective abstraction is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The BFO 2.0 reference provides good examples, like "constant speed profile", "acceleration profile", and "irregular beat profile".
An 'activity profile' of an 'activity' involving rotating equipment, instantiating a class "100 revolutions per minute".

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2 and IDO (and BFO, as mentioned in its documentation) agree that assignment of physical quantities to activities is done through classification. An example of this would be classifying the activity of rotating equipment as "constant 300 rpm." However, they diverge on physical entities. ISO 15926-2, which recognises only 4D entities, mandates the classification approach for any physical entity (see, e.g., the example provided for section 5.2.9.9, p. 129: "... the room was a member of the 20 Celsius property"). IDO (and BFO) represents such assignment using quality individuals dependent on 3D objects; cf. lis:hasPhysicalQuantity and related resources.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An extent of time.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of the notion of time goes beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The moment a valve is closed, upstart time for a motor, the length of time that a bolt has been installed, intervals between maintenance.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000008 is 'temporal region'
An ISO: Realizeable Entity that is realizrd in some OMPD: Hazard Realization Process
An ISO:PhysicalObject hat has a role OMPD:MaintainableItemRole

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An instantaneous part of an 'activity', i.e., its temporal extent is an 'instant'.

primitiveRationale.value: (Here we could consider saying the class is in fact not primitive, but defined in terms of 'activity', 'has temporal extent', and 'instant'.)

example.value: The beginning of a lifting operation, the end of a measurement activity, the midpoint between beginning and end of an activity.

comment.undefined: Event is close in meaning to BFO's 'process boundary', and to DOLCE's 'achievement'. Note that BFO's 'process boundary' is a sibling class to 'process', even though the definition annotation states it to be a "temporal part of a process". It's not obvious why the event/process boundary shouldn't have the same participants as the parent activity/process.
A ISO:InformationObject that  may have some OMPD:ResourceRole

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A potential for participation in activities that is assigned to a bearer, and not inherent to the the bearer's physical make-up.

primitiveRationale.value: Making the notion of assignment (to a task) fully precise is beyond the scope of IDO. With complex intentions notions of obligation, which are often required in role assignments, this is particularly clear.

example.value: The role of an interior space (a 'site') as a meeting room is realized when it serves as the space for conducting meetings. The site may be assigned a storage room role at a different time.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000023 is 'role'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An entity that has some material part.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of what it means to be a physical object is beyond the scope of IDO. There is no obvious consensus on the notion of "material".

example.value: A wall, a fluid stream, a welder, a printed manual, a seafloor.

comment.undefined: IDO asserts that 'physical object' and 'activity' are disjunct classes. In contrast to this, and according to a 4D approach, ISO 15926-2, p. 26, states that "physical_object and activity are not mutually exclusive. A possible_individual can be both".

usageNote.value: The subclasses 'point in space', 'line in space', 'plane in space', and 'volume in space' are all defined as singular: for example, a 'point in space' individual may not have multiple points as parts. This, in contrast to the analogous BFO classes 'one-dimensional spatial region', etc., which are all defined as plural, allowing for disconnected parts.
As with 'spatiotemporal region', a spatial location need not be connected; for example, a location may consist in several cube-shaped regions.
The extent of a 'spatial location' may be given either in terms of a spatial frame of reference, for instance with coordinates, or by position relative to material entities at a point in time.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A determinate region in space.

primitiveRationale.value: To provide an account of space, or frame of reference, is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The cube-shaped region extending 1 metre in each direction from origo, the line extending 10 metres from origo along the z axis, two points with coordinates on a two-dimensional plane; the location of a container at 10:00 AM.

scopeNote.value: The position of a 'spatial location' is fixed (relative to the frame of reference); it is not dependent on changing positions of 'physical object's.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000006 is 'spatial region'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A contiguous, non-separable part of a physical object.

explanatoryNote.value: BFO_0000024 is 'fiat object part'. This is at least very close in meaning to 'feature' as defined in in ISO 15926.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of what "non-separable" means is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A flange face, the inside surface of a pump, a painted area of a manifold, a bolt threading.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A single point in time.

primitiveRationale.value: (Could be considered non-primitive, defined in terms of 'instant region' and 'no proper part'.)

example.value: The moment a valve is closed, the time of a measurement as use for time-stamping, the moment an activity starts.

comment.undefined: 'instant' is defined in OWL Time as "A temporal entity with zero extent or duration".

usageNote.value: The class 'compound' serves as an ultimate "book-keeping" superclass for a taxonomy of material make-up. It has been found useful in managing classifications (of physical objects) according to material composition. It carries no distinguishing constraints, since any physical object will have material composition. The class 'compound' would perhaps better be named "physical object classified according to material composition".

For explicit meaning of a 'compound' subclass, such as "steel [object]", employ an RDL 'quality' class representing "material composition", with restrictions to a modelling construct representing steel.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A physical object with a 'quality' representing material composition.

primitiveRationale.value: The semantics of materials, of which compounds would be a specialisation, is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A volume of complex hydrocarbons, a steel rod, a foam insulation panel; a subclass of compound would in each case contribute the material characterisation.

scopeNote.value: Natural kinds are expressly not to be classified as 'compound'. The class 'compound' is only to be used to classify amounts of matter, with non-semantic auxiliaries used to refer to chemical composition. The semantics of natural kinds such as "helium", "steel", or "hydrocarbon" is out of scope for IDO.

comment.undefined: The "Stream Components" modelling pattern illustrates how a taxonomy of chemical compounds may be used to characterise the 'quality' of material composition.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An individual that has one or more separated (cf. BFO-ISO 'zero-dimensional temporal region') instants as parts.

primitiveRationale.value: (Could be considered non-primitive, defined in terms of 'temporal region' and each part mapping by 'has temporal extent' to 'instant'.)

example.value: The moment a valve is closed, the instants of a series of measurements.

usageNote.value: Artefact types tend to be described primarily in terms of 'function'; for example, the "minimal" definition of a pump would be, "a physical artefact, the function of which is to pump (to be the active participant in a pumping activity)". This kind of definition places no restriction on physical make-up, and is suitable for a subclass of 'functional object'. Note that the activity type of 'pumping' is here a precursor to the definition of the physical object type 'pump'. A taxonomy of pump classes should extend from a class 'pump' defined solely in terms of function, as above.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An 'object' that has a 'function'.

semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom.value: If x is a 'functional object', then x 'has function' some 'function'.

example.value: A pump, a hammer, a stairwell, a pipeline.

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2, p. 110, states, "A functional_physical_object is a physical_object that has functional, rather than material, continuity as its basis for identity. Adjacent temporal parts of a functional_physical_object need not have common matter or energy, provided the matter or energy of each temporal part fulfils the same function."
An ISO:Role that is the role of the item that work is performed on in a OMPD:MaintenanceProcess

usageNote.value: The class 'phase' serves as an ultimate "book-keeping" superclass for a taxonomy of phases.  It carries no distinguishing constraints, since any physical object will have phase.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A physical object with a 'quality' representing a uniformity of physical properties.

primitiveRationale.value: The semantics of phases is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A solid object, a liquid object, a gaseous object.

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2, p. 125: "A phase is a class_of_arranged_individual based on the nature of the boundary behaviour of material resulting from its atomic and molecular bonding."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An object that is made by humans.

primitiveRationale.value: To give a precise account of "making" goes beyond the scope of IDO. An account would engage notions on which there is no clear consensus, including intentional notions of intended purpose, and of goal-directed action; of permanence and integrity; etc.. There is an abundance of edge cases for "artefact".

example.value: Among physical objects, a pressure transmitter, a process plant, a wrench, a computer ; among information objects, a diagram, a PDF document, a software program, a binary file.

comment.undefined: An OMPD:MaintenanceProcess that is: - a direct activity part of zero or one OMPD:MaintenanceProcedureProcess - an activity part of zero or more OMPD:MaintenanceProcedureProcess - a direct activity part of zero or one OMPD:MaintenanceTask - an activity part of zero or more OMPD:MaintenanceTask - occurs directly before zero or one Maintenance task - occurs before zero or more MaintenanceTask - occurs directly after zero or one MaintenanceTask - occurs after zero or more OMPD:MaintenanceTask
An ISO:InformationObject that is about some OMPD:MaintenanceTask

usageNote.value: A scalar quantity datum has a unique unit of measure and a unique numeric value. This class is inspired by the class "scalar measurement datum" of the Information Artefact Ontology.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'quality datum' that represents the magnitude of a 'physical quantity' with a single unit of measure and a single numeric value.

semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom.value: If x is a 'scalar quantity datum', then x is a 'quality datum' which 'quantifies quality' some 'physical quantity', and has a 'datum uom' relationship to a 'unit of measure' and a 'datum value' relationship to a literal value (actually, to a number).

example.value: 10 kilograms, 220 volt.

comment.undefined: IAO_0000032 is 'scalar measurement datum', a class in the Information Artifact Ontology.

usageNote.value: The permissible number range for a scale may be expressed in OWL. Semi-formal example: If 'Celsius' is the 'uom of datum' of x, then any 'datum value' of x is within the range of -273,1 to infinity.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'unit of measure' for which the range of numbers is determinate.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of the notion of scale is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: centimetre, joule per kelvin; nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio scales.

scopeNote.value: Arguably, IDO conflates the notions of "unit of measure" and "scale" in an unhealthy way. While a unit of measure is a definite magnitude, a scale arises from fixing a number range to express multiples of the unit of measure. One may argue that a unit of measure has an implicit scale, obtained by multiplying the unit by any number; this will then allow for undefined or meaningless expressions like "minus 10 Kelvin". The term "Scale" is preserved from ISO 15926-2, which doesn't make use of "unit of measure".

comment.undefined: QUDT provides the following subclasses of 'scale': 'Enumeration scale', 'Interval scale', 'Nominal scale', 'Ordinal scale', 'Ratio scale'. Note that the notion of nominal scales diverges in being a coding scheme, with numbers not implying relative magnitude.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'quality' that can be quantified according to a unit of measure.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of "unit of measure" is employed in the definition of 'physical quantity'. It is beyond the scope of IDO to give an account of measurement.

example.value: The mass of a bar of steel, the temperature of a medium, the inner diameter of a pipe, the lift height of a crane, the head (lift height) of a pump.

comment.undefined: The DOLCE definition of 'physical-quality': "A quality inherent in a physical endurant."

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A two-dimensional, connected 'spatial location'.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of geometries is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The midway horizontal plane of a volume given by coordinates, the plane of a moving work platform at 12:00

usageNote.value: This class is not intended to be used directly, but only for serving as the domain of 'installed as' and similar relations. The disjointness axiom serves to block iterated chains of 'installed as', etc., relationships.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An entity that is part of a specification.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of specification is not defined. An explication should be given in terms of systems engineering practices.

example.value: A "tag" individual, a function of a tag, an activity as characterised in process design.

comment.undefined: A 'prescriptive' individual may be matched with an individual representing an 'actual' individual. Naming for the according relations is tentative: 'installed as' for objects,; 'executed as' for activities; 'implemented by' for dependent entities.
An OMPD: Hazard that is realized in some OMPD: Hazard Realization Process that occurs relative to some OMPD: Maintenance Process

usageNote.value: A common application of 'information object' is in representing facts about the vocabulary of the ontology itself. The OWL facility of "punning" treats OWL classes and properties as OWL individuals, enabling OWL object properties to be applied to them. In use cases that involve punning, the SKOS vocabulary is recommended to be used: the SKOS notions of 'concept', 'concept scheme', and 'collection' should be represented as subclasses of 'information object'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A pattern that 'is about' something else, and 'concretized as' at least one physical entity.

primitiveRationale.value: The definition implicitly calls on the BFO notion of generic dependence, as captured in BFO's 'generically dependent continuant', for which IDO doesn't have an analogue.

example.value: A report, a drawing, a P&ID diagram, a purchase order, a certificate, a database, a database record, a measurement datum, a unit of measure, a SKOS vocabulary.

scopeNote.value: The BFO class 'generically dependent continuant' represents the notion of a pattern that exists in at least one copy, e.g., "the sequence of this protein molecule". This is more general than 'information object', and not at present included in IDO.  'information object' is a subclass, with the added condition that the pattern 'is about' something.

comment.undefined: IAO_0000030 is 'information content entity', a subclass of BFO_0000031 'generically dependent continuant' defined in the Information Artifact Ontology.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'quality' that can be characterised in terms of material phase.

primitiveRationale.value: A precise account of of "material phase" is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The liquid quality of an amount of molten steel, the solid quality of a steel gasket.

comment.undefined: This class is included for coverage of ISO 15926-2, which has 'phase', but many classes don't have a need for it.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An individual that exists only as dependent on an 'object' bearer. 'dependent' individuals enable the ontology to characterise individuals by properties they bear. This is divided into (i) inherent properties ('quality') like colour and mass, and (ii) properties that express potential ('potential'), realized only through participation in activities, like the function of illuminating a space or the role of serving as a boundary.

primitiveRationale.value: To provide necessary and sufficient conditions is beyond scope of IDO. Note that the BFO analogue, 'specifically dependent continuant', is defined in terms of the primitive relation 'specifically depends on' (s-depends on), which is not included in IDO.

scopeNote.value: Any 'object' will be the bearer of various 'dependent' entities, but any 'temporal' entity has only an indirect relationship to 'dependent's. This is in line with BFO, but also a common source of confusion. A common need is to relate a measure based on a 'physical quantity' to an 'activity', like average speed to a transport activity; this may not be implemented as an "average speed" dependent entity of the transport. For a suitable representation pattern, see the class 'activity profile' and related resources.

example.value: The colour of a surface, the temperature of a medium, the storage-space role of a room.

comment.undefined: The class Dependent is closely related to "specifically dependent continuant" in BFO (BFO_0000020).
A ISO:PhysicalObject that may have some OMPD:ResourceRole

usageNote.value: The typical 'function' of a hammer is realized when the hammer participates as the tool in a successful nail-driving activity. If the hammer has multiple functions, such as extracting nails using a claw or shaping objects with a ball, each function should be represented with a distinct individual.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: A 'capability' which is the reason for existence of the bearer. The bearer's physical design (or evolved form, in the case of natural biological entities) is there in order to enable participation in activities of the specified kind, in a specified way.

primitiveRationale.value: Making the notion of purpose, or "existence for being", fully precise is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: The capability of a motor to apply torque to a shaft.

comment.undefined: Inspired by the BFO class "function" (BFO_0000034).
A ISO:PhysicalObject that  may have some OMPD:ResourceRole

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: An actual individual that serves as a prescriptive object for some period of time.

explanatoryNote.value: The class 'installed object' should be considered defined as "an individual that may appear on the left side of an 'installed as' relationship". It is in this sense not primitive.

primitiveRationale.value: A full account of the nature of prescription or specification, and actual implementation is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A concrete, serial-numbered artefact that is installed as a "tag" is the paradigm of 'installed object'. See examples for 'prescriptive object'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has assembled part' y, then y is a connected 'arranged part' of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of connection is primitive.

example.value: A pipe bend welded into a piping spool, the protective sheath on an electrical cable, a door-handle in a door.

usageNote.value: 'has functional part' is used to represent the functional break-down of a system. Where x is a functional part of a system y, the realisation of one or more functions of x contributes to the performance of y.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has functional part' y, then x is a 'system' of which y is a part, and y has one or more functions that contribute to the function of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of "contributing function" is not fully accounted for in IDO; a proper explanation might require an account of parts of functions themselves, i.e., of how simple functions can be composed into complex functions.

example.value: A separation system has a cooling system as functional part.

usageNote.value: This is a covering relation for passive participation, i.e., being acted on by other participants in an activity, or playing a supporting role.

With OWL property chains, the right kind of participation can be secured for activities that count as realizations of 'potential' individuals. As in, a bolt is a passive participant in a bolt-driving activity, where its disposition to enter a threaded hole is realized (distinct from the bolt's function, which is realized in a subsequent activity of holding pieces together).

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: if x 'has passive participant' y, then x is a passive participant in y.

primitiveRationale.value: The distinction between active and participation participation is primitive.

example.value: A metal plate is perforated in a drilling activity, a volume of liquid is heated in a heat transmission activity, a loading ramp is the location of an offloading activity, a fluid medium is pumped, a piece of metal is shaped, a stream of data is filtered.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'datumUOM'.

comment.undefined: Relation from 'unit of measure' to 'quantity datum'. The inverse relation of datumUOM.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has quality' y, then x is an 'object', and y is a 'quality' that is dependent on x.

primitiveRationale.value: The relation of dependence is a not defined in IDO.

example.value: A motor has rated output power, a lightbulb has luminance, an amount of liquid has mass, a bar of metal has chemical composition, a document has readability.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000196 is 'bearer of', a more generic relation than 'has quality' in that its range is any 'specifically dependent continuant', which in IDO corresponds to 'dependent'.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has active participant'.

Assume y is an 'activity profile', obtained from some containing activity z by selective abstraction on a quality q of a participant in z. Then, relate y by 'profile quantity datum' to magnitudes of q that are recorded during the execution of y.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x has 'profile quanity datum' y, then x is an 'activity profile', y is a 'quality datum', and at a time within the duration of x, y quantifies [TODO. rewrite with a different term than "quantifies"] a quality of a participant in x.

primitiveRationale.value: TODO (revisit). The notion of "during" used here goes beyond OWL expressivity.

example.value: The pressure of a liquid is measured at 10, 11, and 12 bar at different points of time during a transport activity.

comment.undefined: Intuitively, 'profile quantity datum' should only point to quantity data recorded while the activity is taking place. This can not be enforced with OWL restrictions on the relation (it would require a "diamond" pattern). However, with a suitable date or time data property value restriction, an individual activity can constrain related quantity data.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has spatial extent'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'resides in'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has arranged part'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'directly connected to' y, then x is 'connected to' y, and any material present between x and y directly serves to maintain the connection.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of maintaining connection is not defined; what counts as a direct connection is hard to define precisely.

example.value: An electrical plug is connected to a socket, a tag plate is welded to a pressure vessel.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has capability' y if and only if x 'has potential' y, and y is a 'capability'.

example.value: A pressure sensor has the capability of being a level sensor, a wall has the capability of noise insulation.

comment.undefined: In the OBO Foundry, we find 'has capability' included only in the Semanticscience Integrated Ontology (SIO), with identifier http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000586. In SIO, 'has capability' is a superrelation to 'has disposition', which is the inverse of what is given in IDO.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'profile of quality'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has activity bound' y, then x 'has activity part' y, and y is an 'event'.

example.value: The moment an electrical connection is broken, the time that a fluid reaches a set temperature.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has sublocation' y, then x and y are locations, and x 'has part' y.

example.value: The landing area is a sublocation of the helicopter deck.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'is about'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has physical quantity' y if and only if x 'has quality' y, and y is a 'physical quantity'.

example.value: A section of pipe has length, a crane has lifting power, a flange has inner diameter.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'site of' y, then x is a 'site', y is an 'activity', and y takes place entirely within x.

primitiveRationale.value: x 'site of' y means, the spatial extent of the site contains the spatial extent of the activity for the duration of the activity. This requires a relation of "spatial projection throughout the time of the activity", which is not included in IDO. (The BFO-ISO definition expresses this using the temporalized relation 'spatially projects onto at all times'.)

example.value: Mixing takes place within a vessel, transport takes place in a pipeline

comment.undefined: BFO_0000217 is 'spatially projects onto at all times'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'causes' y, then x is an 'activity' that is 'before' the 'event' y, and x causes y to happen.

primitiveRationale.value: The temporal vocabulary is primitive.

example.value: The tanker loading activity caused the event described as 'tank liquid level full' (example from ISO 15926-2, p. 127)

comment.undefined: This relation is too specialised to warrant inclusion in IDO.

usageNote.value: This relation is "abstract" (in the object-orientation sense of the word) in that it serves only as a parent relation to specialised relations. It is intended to serve as a super-property for "shortcut" relations that combine a quality, lis:qualityQuantifiedAs, and a unit of measure into a simple data property.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x has 'quality quantity value' y, then x is an 'object', and y is the 'datum value' of a 'quality datum' that 'quantifies quality' a 'quality' of x.

example.value: Mass in kilograms, pressure in barg.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has functional part'.
The 'site' of an object will occupy different 'spatial location's over time if the location and size of the object changes.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has spatial extent' y, then x is a 'physical object', and y is the 'site' determined as the extension in space of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of "spatial extension" an object is not fully defined.

example.value: The volume occupied by an process skid, the volume occupied by a volume of flammable gas.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000210 is 'occupies spatial region at some time' (from BFO-ISO) (paired with BFO_0000211 'occupies spatial region at all times'), with 'spatial region' as range, which is incompatible with 'has spatial extent' in IDO, where the range is 'site'.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'creates'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has assembled part'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has interest' y if and only if x 'has potential' y, and y is an 'interest'.

explanatoryNote.value: The relation of interest receives a related, but different treatment in Merrell, et al., "Capabilities" (cf. annotations on 'capability'), p. 14: "We take the 'has an interest in' relation to be primitive, ... [T]he domain of this relation is: all organisms and groups of organisms, ... [T]he range is process in BFO terms, specifically all processes that are the realizations of dispositions." With IDO, the range is instead a 'potential'; this allows for interests that are not realized.

example.value: An intention to start a process, a plan to modify a plant, an approval of a certification.

comment.undefined: Derived from the relation "LifecycleStage" of ISO 15926-2, which has the attribute pair 'interest'/'interested'; "ClassOfLifecycleStage" provides examples of specialisations as, "EXAMPLE Planned, required, expected, and proposed can be represented by instances of [class_of_lifecycle_stage]." Following this, 'interest of' is a superproperty suitable for various intentional relationships, such as planning, approving, or ordering. With IDO, we restrict interest to 'potential' entities, while in ISO 15926-2 the domain and range are both unrestricted.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has physical quantity'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has quality'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has interest'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has activity part' y, then x and y are activities, and x 'has arranged part' y.

scopeNote.value: Parts of activities may be determined by a range of criteria, including temporal restrictions (to sub-periods), spatial restrictions (parts that occupy sub-volumes of space), by the engagement of participants (temporal or spatial parts where one or more participants are active), and "selective abstraction" to profiles (parts determined by that which affects variation in selected qualities).

example.value: The startup period of a chemical process, the survey part of a maintenance activity, the moment a software program terminates execution.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000117 is 'has occurrent part' in BFO-ISO. This relation has 'occurrent' as domain and range, where the IDO 'has activity part' is restricted to just 'activity'.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of literal value is primitive.

example.value: The measured datum "55 degrees Celsius" has "55" as literal value.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000055 is 'realizes' in BFO-ISO.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'installed as'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has activity profile' y, then x 'has activity part' y, and y is determined by selective abstraction to that part of x that effects variation in some quality of a participant in x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of selective abstraction is not defined.

example.value: A pipeline transport activity has a "profile" part which is the variation in fluid pressure.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000133 is 'process profile of', in the Molecular Process Ontology and other BFO-based ontologies.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has arranged part' y, then y is a part of x with a boundary determined in relation to other parts of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of determinate boundary is taken as primitive. See the account of "fiat part" in BFO documentation.

example.value: The upper half of a pressure vessel, the mid-section of a bridge.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000024 is 'fiat object part' in BFO-ISO.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has ending'.
The mechanism for checking requirement consistency on 'installed as' relationships must be implemented as a transformation that is external to the OWL ontology.
Periods of 'installed as' relationships should be recorded using OWL annotations, to enable prescriptive objects to be matched with installed objects for selected points or periods in time.

An asset model with 'installed as' relationships supports compatibility checks for installed objects, to uncover possible violations of requirements.  This is requires a transformation of the asset model, as follows: replace each 'installed as' relationship with identity (owl:sameAs), and replace classifications as 'prescriptive object' or 'installed object' with just 'object' for the participant individuals.  Any semantic inconsistency between the the prescriptive object and the installed object may then be discovered by OWL reasoning.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'installed as' y, then x and y are 'object's, and at some time, x is the same individual as y.

explanatoryNote.value: The 'installed as' relation is declared asymmetric with an OWL restriction. This ensures that or that the relation can't go both ways, and implies an individual may not be 'installed as' itself (asymmetry implies irreflexivity). Furthermore, the domain and range restrictions to disjunct classes 'installed object' and 'prescriptive object' prevent chains of 'installed as' relationships.

primitiveRationale.value: 'has installed' is used to express identity relationships that may vary over time. Because OWL lacks time indices, the representation is informal.

scopeNote.value: The 'installed as' relation is central to the intended use of IDO. It allows for a record of different individuals being installed over time. Typically, a serial-numbered artefact is installed as a 'prescriptive' individual (a "tag") at one time, and later replaced with another serial-numbered artefact. The 'installed as' relation carries semantic restrictions only to ensure no object is both installed and prescriptive. No further constraints are given, to allow 'installed as' relationships even where restrictions on the prescriptive object are inconsistent with those on the installed object.

example.value: Pump P-101 is a tag, and ACME pumps with serial numbers 457636 and 457711 have been installed as this pump.

usageNote.value: This relation is "abstract" (in the object-orientation sense of the word) in that it serves only as a parent relation to specialised relations of relative temporal location. [TODO improve; any 'temporal' has temporal location, so the definition is trivial.]

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'occurs relative to' y, then x and y are 'temporal' entities, with temporal location.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of relative location in time is introduced with this relation.

example.value: A vessel is emptied before inspection, a valve is opened before draining of a pipeline, firmware is installed before the equipment begins to operate.

comment.undefined: This relation is introduced for the DL profile as a top relation for various temporal relations between activities (only).

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'realized in' y, then x is a 'potential', and y is an 'activity' that successfully realizes x.

primitiveRationale.value: A full account of the notion of "successfully realizes" is beyond the scope of IDO. It depends on an account of "success", in that failed activities will not be realizations, and on the bearer of the potential participating in the realizing activity in the right way.

example.value: A pump realizes its function in a pumping (activity), a bolt realizes its function in a connection, a software monitoring application realizes its function in streaming sensor data.

primitiveRationale.value: Parthood is a main primitive for ontologies.

example.value: A system has functional parts, a process has stages, a plant is partitioned into areas.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000117 is 'has occurrent part' in BFO-ISO.
The notion of approval will only be employed in a limited range of use-cases, and is therefore too specific to be included in IDO. It may be defined in a domain-specific RDL.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'is about' y, then x is an 'information object' of relevance to y.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive account of aboutness is beyond the scope of IDO.

scopeNote.value: The 'is about' relation is intended as a superrelation for the broad range of relations between information objects and entities, including describing, naming, characterisation, and evaluation.

example.value: A regulation describes a procedure, a datum quantifies a quality, a nameplate provides basic information about a pressure vessel, a log file traces quantity values during an activity.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of non-separable and contiguous part is primitive.

example.value: A flange face, a corrosion protected surface, the contact surface of an electrical plug.

comment.undefined: The definition is lifted directly from 'feature whole part ' of ISO 15926-2.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has role'.

comment.undefined: RO_0000081 is 'role of' in the Relations Ontology.

usageNote.value: Assume p is a pump, a an activity that realizes the function fp of p, and no subactivity x of a realizes fp (except for subactivities determined solely by restriction to a temporal sub-interval). For instance, the subactivity of the motor that drives the impeller realizes a function of the motor, but this is not by itself a realization of the function of the pump as a whole, hence the motor is not a 'primary participant'.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of being "located within" is not fully defined here, leaving open whether this is understood in terms of boundaries of physical objects or a fixed frame of reference.

example.value: An engine is located in a machine room, a pressure vessel is located in an outdoors plant area.

usageNote.value: 'has functional part' is used to represent the functional break-down of a system. Where x is a functional part of a system y, the realisation of one or more functions of x contributes to the performance of y.

However, in OWL, an object property with property chain restrictions may not be combined with cardinality restrictions. Correct cardinalities must therefore be maintained with rules external to the ontology.

example.value: A temperature activity profile of a heating process represents just that part of the process which is a variation in temperature.

The relation of concretization is under-documented, especially when it comes to concretization as entities to be realized in activities, or activities themselves; we follow the latter, as is done in BFO-ISO, where the performance of a musical piece is the concretization. Other BFO documentation says the intention to perform is the concretization.  The current annotations and axioms in IDO represent a best effort, but may need to be changed.

There are two main, and very different, uses of 'concretizes' for an information object y.  (1) The information object is made concrete in printed or electronic copies. Each copy will have patterns of ink or configurations of electrons that map to y: a quality of appropriate similarity.  (2) The information object is made concrete by a performance according to the specification given by y. A 'process profile' of the performance will map to the pattern of y in an appropriate way.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'concretizes' y, then y is an 'information object', and x is a 'physical object' copy of y, or an 'activity' performance of y.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of what it means to be a copy, or manifest a pattern, is beyond the scope of IDO. The definition given here is clearly incomplete.

example.value: A report is produced as paper copies, a spreadsheet document is shown on a computer screen, a plan is carried out, a device operates according to a functional specification, a software program is executed.

scopeNote.value: Inspired by BFO's "concretizes". The constraints on 'concretizes' in IDO closely matches that employed in BFO-ISO (obo:BFO_0000059), and not the RO or the IAO (obo:RO_0000059).

comment.undefined: RO_0000059 is 'concretizes', from the Relations Ontology; also used in the Information Artifact Ontology.

usageNote.value: This relation is "abstract" (in the object-orientation sense of the word) in that it serves only as a parent relation to specialized relations of relative location. [TODO improve; any object has location in space, so the definition is trivial.]

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'located relative to' y, then x and y are 'object's with location in space.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of relative location in space is introduced with this relation.

example.value: An outlet is below an inlet, a door is inside an opening, a motor is inside an enclosure.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000171 is 'located in at some time' in BFO-ISO. This relation has domain and range restricted to 'independent continuant' and not 'spatial region', meaning it's a relation between entities that are material objects or determined by material objects, only.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has spatiotemporal extent' y, then x is an activity, and y is a spatiotemporal region which is the spatiotemporal extent of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of spatiotemporal extension is primitive.

example.value: A pipeline pig occupies the spatiotemporal region which is its trajectory (adopted from BFO-ISO).

comment.undefined: BFO_0000200 is 'occupies spatiotemporal region'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: if x 'creates' y, then x is an 'activity', y is an 'object', and x brings y into being.

primitiveRationale.value: A comprehensive definition of the notion of creation is beyond the scope of IDO.

example.value: A manufacturing activity produces a car, a welding activity produces a piping spool, a measurement activity produces a performance log.

comment.undefined: ISO 15926-2, p. 132 provides an example as, "A car manufacturing activity causes the beginning of a car" ).

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has role' y if and only if x 'has potential' y, and y is a 'role'.

example.value: An window has the role of a ventilation opening, a room has the role of a storage space, a gas sensor has the role of a leak detector, a person has the role of inspector.

comment.undefined: Inspired by BFO's "has role" (RO_0000087)

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'connected to' y, then there is a physical connection between x and y.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of being connected to is primitive; an account would require an account of connection activities and constancy of material objects between the connected individuals.

example.value: A three-pin electrical plug is connected to a three-pin socket, a drip pipe is indirectly connected to a drain funnel (examples from ISO 15926-2), two flanges are connected with bolts and a gasket.

comment.undefined: RO_0002170 is 'connected to', in the Relations Ontology.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has temporal extent'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has participant'.

A property chain axiom secures that when a realizable (a 'disposition' or 'role') is 'realized in' an activity, the activity has the bearer as a participant. [TODO required participation may not be appropriate for 'interest's]
A property chain axiom secures that when an activity has a 'profile quantity datum', the bearer of the quantity is a participant in the activity.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has participant' y, then x is an 'activity', and y is an 'object' that participates in x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of participation is primitive.

example.value: A pump participates in (a) pumping (activity), an electric transformer participates in voltage conversion, a stream of water participates in dilution, a bolt participates in a connection.

comment.undefined: A property chain axiom secures that a participant in part of an activity participates in the activity as a whole.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x is 'before' y, then x ends no later than the start of y.

primitiveRationale.value: The temporal vocabulary is primitive.

example.value: The cooling stage takes place before separation.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000063 is 'precedes' in BFO-ISO.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'approves'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has activity profile'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has part'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'represented by'.

comment.undefined: Since we have the pair 'is about'/'represented in', it appears unnecessary to retain 'represents' and 'represented by' just for the link to ISO 15926-2.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has ending' y, then y is an 'event' which 'has temporal extent' some 'instant' which is the last instant of the temporal extent of x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of last instant is not defined.

example.value: The event that light is switched off, the end of filling a tank.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000224 is 'has last instant' in BFO-ISO, defined for 'temporal region' (differently from 'has ending' in IDO, defined for 'activity').

The Time Ontology https://www.w3.org/TR/owl-time/ introduces several data properties to annotate Instants with their time positions (including time:inXSDDateTimeStamp etc). The lis:timestamp property allows to directly add timestamps to events, without resorting to Instant objects that are temporal extents of an event.  We may also add two subproperties lis:startTimestamp and lis:endTimestamp.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has capability'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has feature'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has datum uom' y, then x is a 'quality datum' for which any 'datum value' is interpreted by the 'unit of measure' y.

primitiveRationale.value: Interpretation in terms of a unit is not defined.

example.value: The measured datum "55 degrees Celsius" has Celsius as unit of measure.

comment.undefined: RO_0002536 is 'measurement property has unit', an annotation property in the Relations Ontology.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has function' y if and only if x 'has potential' y, and y is a 'function'.

example.value: A pump has the function of moving fluids, a door has the function of an explosion barrier.

comment.undefined: Inspired by BFO's 'has function' (RO_0000085). Note that this relation is defined in the Relation Ontology (RO, https://oborel.github.io/) and is not included in BFO-ISO, which provides the more generic 'inheres in' (BFO_0000197). Furthermore, in RO 'has function' is a sibling of 'has disposition', not a subrelation.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has quality' y, then x is an 'object', and y is a 'quality' that is dependent on x.

primitiveRationale.value: The relation of dependence is a not defined in IDO.

example.value: A motor has rated output power, a lightbulb has luminance, an amount of liquid has mass, a bar of metal has chemical composition, a document has readability.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000196 is 'bearer of', a more generic relation than 'has quality' in that its range is any 'specifically dependent continuant', which in IDO corresponds to 'dependent'.

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: x 'has function' y if and only if x 'has potential' y, and y is a 'function'.

example.value: A pump has the function of moving fluids, a door has the function of an explosion barrier.

comment.undefined: Inspired by BFO's 'has function' (RO_0000085). Note that this relation is defined in the Relation Ontology (RO, https://oborel.github.io/) and is not included in BFO-ISO, which provides the more generic 'inheres in' (BFO_0000197). Furthermore, in RO 'has function' is a sibling of 'has disposition', not a subrelation.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has disposition'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'causes'.

comment.undefined: This relation is too specialised to warrant inclusion in IDO.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'concretizes'.
This relation is intended to be used where an object x is located inside another object y, but x not is not a part of y (as would be the case, e.g., for an assembly).

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'contains' y, then x and y are 'physical object's, and y is located entirely within x.

primitiveRationale.value: The notion of being "located within" is not fully defined here, leaving open whether this is understood in terms of boundaries of physical objects or a fixed frame of reference.

example.value: An instrument is contained in an enclosure, an pump contains an impeller, a device is contained by a volume of inert gas, a pipeline inspection gauge (pig) is located inside a pipeline.

comment.undefined: BFO_0000124 is 'location of at some time' in BFO-ISO.

usageNote.value: This is a covering relation for participation that involves acting on other participants.

With OWL property chains, the right kind of participation can be secured for activities that count as realizations of 'potential' individuals. As in, a pump's primary function is realized in pumping activities, but only provided the pump is actually doing the pumping, acting as an "agent" or "subject".

naturalLanguageDefinition.value: If x 'has active participant' y, then x is an active participant in y.

primitiveRationale.value: The distinction between active and participation participation is primitive.

example.value: A hammer is the tool in a nail-driving activity, a pressure transmitter outputs data in a monitoring activity, a maintenance engineer replaces an instrument in a repair activity, a light sensor controls the level of illumination.

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has passive participant'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has potential'.

comment.undefined: This relation is used in the property chain for 'has participant', for inferring participation in a temporal entity (typically, an activity).

usageNote.value: For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has function'.
For annotations, see the inverse relation 'has sub location'.
